Here the young poet failed to act up to his Stoic training¹: under the fear of death his constancy gave way, and after holding out for a while he charged his own mother Acilia with a share in the plot.

But neither this nor a string of confessions² which followed could save him: he was soon like the rest condemned to die, the mode of death being left to his own choice. Accordingly he nerved himself for his end, went into ahot bath and had his veins opened³: there he calmly bled to death in the same way as many other Romans of mark did in those days of tyranny when suicide was the only refuge from despair. While the life-blood ran from him he is said to have repeated aloud some appropriate lines from his own great poem (tx. 811-814):

sanguis eraut lacrimae: quaecunque foramina novit humor, ab his largus manat cruor: ora redundant et patulae nares: sudor rubet: omnia plenis membra fluunt venis: totum est pro vulnere corpus.

Thus died Lucam and his uncle Seneca and his father Mela‘ were involved in the same ruin.
